        <h1>Monitoring</h1>
        <p>The monitoring system allows the ALIVE framework to exchange, store and generate events. The events can be generated by various causes, being the main one the interactions of the agents on the coordination level. Such interactions can either be agents communicating with another agent, or agents enacting services on the service level. </p>
        <p> Events are submitted via the <em><a href="http://org.eclipse.ui.intro/showPage?id=eventbus">event bus</a></em> component so they can be captured and processed by the different elements on the monitoring system, that is:</p>
        <p> <a href="http://org.eclipse.ui.intro/showPage?id=eventlog">Event log</a>: this component is responsible for capturing relevant events from the <em>event bus</em> and storing them in a persistent support (such as a database) so they can be queried later by another ALIVE components.</p>
        <p> <a href="http://org.eclipse.ui.intro/showPage?id=monitor">Monitor</a>: this component is responsible for capturing relevant events from the <em>event bus</em> and interpreting them based on a set of rules (<em>counts as rules</em>) and norms specified on the ALIVE <em>organisational model</em>. This interpretation can generate new events (either <em>high level events</em> from the <em>counts as </em>rules or <em>violation events</em> from the norms) that are submitted to the <em>event bus</em>.</p>
        <p> <a href="http://org.eclipse.ui.intro/showPage?id=monitortool">Monitor tool</a>: this component has been designed to enable end users to query and visualize the events that have been submitted in one or more ALIVE systems. The <em>monitor tool</em> can read events from different <em>event bus </em>and <em>event log</em> components, and show information related to the events (sender, receiver, conceptâ€¦) in a visual user-friendly way.</p>
